e of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."],"variants":[{"name":"Sey","meanings":["English and Scottish: probably a variant of   Say   particularly prevalent in Scotland.","Dutch and Flemish: from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigiheri</i> (see   Seger  ).","West African (Ghana): Akan (Fante) name of unexplained etymology."]},{"name":"Sayer","meanings":["English: common occupational name from Middle English <i>sayer</i>, a phonetic variant of   Sawyer  , which in Wales and neighboring English counties may have been reinforced by the synonymous Welsh <i>saer</i> ‘carpenter’ and everywhere by a possible borrowing into Middle English of Old French <i>seieor</i>, <i>saieur</i> ‘sawyer’.","English: rare occupational name perhaps denoting an assayer of metals, or a servant who tasted his lord's food before serving, from Middle English <i>saiour</i> ‘assayer, tester’ (a shortened form of Old French <i>assaiour</i>, ultimately from Late Latin <i>exagium</i>, a derivative of <i>exagmināre</i> ‘to weigh’).","English: rare occupational name for a professional reciter or minstrel, from Middle English <i>seier(e)</i> ‘speaker’."]},{"name":"Saye","meanings":["English: variant of   Say  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Saje</b>: nickname for someone with very dark, sooty hair, derived from the root of <i>sajast</i> ‘sooty’, or directly from <i>saja</i> ‘soot’.","West African (Liberia): from the personal name <i>Saye</i>, found among the Mano (Mah) people, denoting a first-born boy."]}]},{"name":"Baroness","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Nels.","Norwegian: old variant of <b>Barsnes</b> (and, in North America, probably also an altered form of this), a habitational name from a farmstead so named in the county of Sogn og Fjordane, possibly from a compound of the Old Norse personal name <i>Baldrekr</i> + <i>nes</i> ‘point, headland’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":2,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Anne Wentworth Say, Baroness Despencer was born in 1453, in Nettlestead, Suffolk, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Henry Wentworth. She died before October 1494, in her hometown."},"et":{"1453–before October 1494":"1453–enne oktoobrit 1494","1432–1501":"1432–1501","1476–1545":"1476–1545","1453–1494":"1453–1494","before October 1494":"enne oktoobrit 1494","1545":"1545","1501":"1501","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1432":"1432","1453":"1453","22 July 1476":"22. juuli 1476","1494":"1494","Nettlestead, Suffolk, England":"Nettlestead, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1453–before October 1494":"1453–ennen vuotta lokakuu 1494","1432–1501":"1432–1501","1476–1545":"1476–1545","1453–1494":"1453–1494","before October 1494":"ennen vuotta lokakuu 1494","1545":"1545","1501":"1501","1455":"1455","1